desc.eadoc:name: EvidenceTypeList
desc.eadoc:note: A collection of types of evidences. Additional information The respondent of a Requirement for which one or more types of evidences have been specified in an EvidenceTypeList is expected to provide Evidence(s) conformant to that type of evidence. This list is use to build "combinations" of assets; e.g., in a Request for Evidences you could have: List-1: EvidencType-1 AND EvidenceType-2 AND EvidenceType-3; OR List-2: EvidencType-1 AND EvidenceType-5 AND EvidenceType-4;

desc.eadoc:name: Constraint
desc.eadoc:note: Limitation applied to requirement(s) or to the concept(s) the requirement is about. Additional Information: An example in eProcurement, a threshold: the minimum Turnover required by the buyer to select the candidates.

desc.eadoc:name: Criterion
desc.eadoc:note: A condition for evaluation or assessment. Additional Information: In general, criteria are used for comparison, filtering and selection. Criteria usually set minimum constraints (e.g. limits, intervals, thresholds, etc.) that need to be met in order to pass the required conditions or to fulfil them in a certain degree or quality. The evaluation of the fulfilment is usually supported with the provision of evidences.

desc.eadoc:name: InformationRequirement
desc.eadoc:note:
A request for data that is proof of evidence or leads to the source of such a proof.
Additional Information:
The response to an information requirement is an evidence when the issuer of the response is an authoritative source (a.k.a. ‘source of truth’, e.g. a Civil Registry providing data about a natural person for the provision of public service through the Single Digital Gateway). In other cases the responses might not be issued by an authoritative source but the issuer supports the responses with evidences (or commits to support them timely, e.g. a self-declaration or a declaration of oath).

desc.eadoc:name: EvidenceType
desc.eadoc:note: Information about the characteristics of an expected evidence, such as the desired content, format, source, etc. Evidence types can be seen as ‘templates’ that actual evidences need to use to express the data that constitutes the proof.

desc.eadoc:name: Concept
desc.eadoc:note: A reference to an entity, i.e. a class or a property, which is defined in a known ontology or vocabulary. Additional information: A concept defined in the context of a Requirement must be unambiguous so there is no possibility of misinterpretation. Hence the use of qualified names (a pair {namespace, local name} is strongly recommended for the identification of the entity being referred to.

desc.eadoc:name: ReferenceFramework
desc.eadoc:note: A source from where requirements are identified and drawn. Additional Information Usual reference frameworks are legal and non-legal specifications. Examples of reference frameworks can be, the ELI Legal Resources used for the BREG catalogue of datasets, the basis for the ISA2 CAMSS Scenarios such as the Regulation (EU) 1025/2012 or the EIF Framework, the European Directives used in e-Certis and the ESPD Implementing Regulation for the identification of exclusion grounds and selection criteria, a standard, a technical specification, etc.

desc.eadoc:name: Evidence
desc.eadoc:note: The data proving that a requirement is met or has been fulfilled. Additional Information: Evidences are usually references to a record, or the record content itself, used to prove the veracity of a requirement fulfilment. The concept of 'record' herein is to be understood as it used for records management: a digital object that is considered final (e.g. not a working document) and cannot be altered. Examples of evidences can be a stream of data value or values provided by a base registry, a structured official e-certificate issued by a public authority, an unstructured document (e.g. a PDF) provided by an authorised service provider acting on behalf of an authority, other. Source: based on the ePO definition of Evidence.

desc.eadoc:name: Requirement
desc.eadoc:note: A condition demanded. Additional Information: Generic class representing any type of prerequisite that may be desired, needed or imposed as an obligation. The European Directive on services in the internal market1 defines requirement as any obligation, prohibition, condition or limit provided for in exercise of their legal autonomy [..]”. Source: based on the Collins English Dictionary, accessed through TheFreeDictionary.com hub.------------------------- 1 See Directive 2006/123/EU, Article 4(7), ‘Requirements’.: https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/PDF/?uri=CELEX:32006L0123&from=EN.

desc.eadoc:name: Dataset
desc.eadoc:note: The latest version 2.2 relates one Dataset to another through the inherited axioms "dcat:Resource dcat:qualifiedRelation dcat:Relationship" and "dcat:Relationship dct:relation dcat:Dataset".
